
Rajen Sheth is a product manager of Google enterprise.[tpl]cite web|title=Google, Microsoft on collision course, but users could benefit.|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-151179505.html|publisher=Highbeam|accessdate=14 April 2012[/tpl]  The idea of Google's email service Gmail was pitched by Rajen in a meeting with CEO Eric Schmidt in 2004. Schmidt primarily rejected the proposal, and argued the division should focus on web search. But finally the proposal of creating Google's email service was accepted. He is known as "father of Google Apps.[tpl]cite news|title=Chromebook: ‘Father of Google Apps’ Raises Second Child|url=http://www.wired.com/wiredenterprise/2011/10/chromebook-raises-second-child/|publisher=http://www.wired.com/|accessdate=14 April 2012|first=Cade|last=Metz|date=7 October 2011[/tpl] He is also responsible for development of Chrome and Chrome OS for Business.[tpl]cite web|title=Rajen Sheth, Group Product Manager, Chrome for Business|url=https://sites.google.com/a/pressatgoogle.com/chromepress/Home/google-i-o-news/i-o-spokespeople/sheth-bio|publisher=Chrome Media Center|accessdate=14 April 2012[/tpl][tpl]cite web|title=Click here to find out more! One on One: Rajen Sheth of Google Chrome|url=http://smallbiztrends.com/2011/07/one-on-one-rajen-sheth-of-google-chrome.html|publisher=http://smallbiztrends.com/|accessdate=14 April 2012|author=Brent Leary|date=15|month=July|year=2011[/tpl]

==Career==

Rajen studied Computer Engineering (1994-1999) in Stanford University like Sergey Brin and Larry Page. He graduated with Electrical Engineering and got a master’s degree in Computer Engineering from Stanford University in 1999 and then joined Microsoft. At that time, Microsoft was reshaping their email service, Hotmail. After a year at Microsoft, he moved to a Silicon Valley startup known as Zaplet, where he built what he calls “future email technologies.” In 2004, he joined Google.

